\par\par \b \uc2 Ensuring aid effectiveness   \b0\par\par\uc2 765 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 January 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) predictably approved on Thursday US$2.8 billion in new loans and $600 million in new grants to help the government plug part of the big hole in its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 It is roughly similar to the pledges made by the creditor group last year, but the sum is less than half of the $7.2 billion the government has to transfer overseas in debt service payments this year.   \par \par \uc2 On top of these pledges, the creditor consortium also committed $1.7 billion in soft loans and grants especially for the rehabilitation and reconstruction of Aceh.   \par \par \uc2 Since 2003, the government's annual debt service payments overseas have been more than twice as large as its new foreign borrowing, because the government is no longer entitled to a debt rescheduling facility from its sovereign creditors and more debts are now maturing.   \par \par \uc2 However small the new pledges may seem, compared to the annual interest charges and debt amortization, the new aid commitments will nonetheless help greatly, especially now as the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  burdens have sharply increased after the cataclysm in northern Sumatra.   \par \par \uc2 The terms and conditions of CGI loans are concessional in that their \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are way below what the government can obtain from the international financial market and their maturity extends to as long as 40 years, including a 10-year grace period. More than one-fifth of the pledges consist of grants.   \par \par \uc2 For example, the $1.07 billion in new pledges made by Japan, Indonesia's largest sovereign creditor, carry annual \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  of only between 0.4 to 1.3 percent a year, as compared to the more than 10 percent, which the government has to pay for its ten-year global bonds that were floated last year. Even the \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  charged by the World Bank and Asian Development Bank, which raise their lending resources from the capital market, are more than 5 percentage points lower than the government's borrowing costs.   \par \par \uc2 Moreover, the CGI loans are used entirely for sectors, which promise high productivity and high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns, but which are not attractive to private investors, such as basic infrastructure like roads, ports and water networks, as well as education and health facilities.   \par \par \uc2 However, as past experiences have shown, what is more important is not the amount of pledges, but how well the soft loans are used. Tens of billions of dollars in past CGI loan commitments had been cancelled due to long delays in their disbursement, caused mainly by problems on the part of the government: lack of counterpart funds, poor project preparations and some confusion in the division of responsibility between the central and local governments.   \par \par \uc2 On top of these problems, the long delay in the establishment of a national \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  procurement office has undermined project implementation. Analysts can only scratch their heads and wonder why such an important agency, which can simply be set up with a presidential decree, is taking so much time to establish, while \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  procurement of goods and services has long been a main source of corruption both at government institutions and state companies.   \par \par \uc2 No wonder good governance practices are the primary condition to which creditors tie their aid pledges. Almost all major donors reiterated last week the importance of corruption eradication. The primary reason, as ADB Vice President Joseph Eichenberger noted, is quite obvious: The donors have to prove to their own taxpayers (in the case of government creditors) and their shareholders (in the case of multilateral donors) that the money is used for the purposes intended.   \par \par \uc2 This condition makes a lot of sense because the creditors would simply waste their money and make the new debts completely unsustainable if the government did not improve governance practices and implement projects according to schedules.   \par \par \uc2 In fact, problems related to bad governance practices and poor infrastructure have been cited as the main barriers to private investment. Various surveys have found that costs associated with \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and regulatory \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and unreliable infrastructure amounted to as large as 20 percent of company sales.   \par \par \uc2 President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono personally reemphasized the vital role of good governance and good quality infrastructure in his address at the CGI meeting, and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministers elaborated on key reforms that were planned to improve the investment climate.   \par \par \uc2 The market and investors, which have often been disillusioned with false starts in reform programs, expect immediate, concrete implementation of these promises, lest even the Susilo government, supported by a strong political mandate, would not be able to seize upon the emerging cyclical upturn so the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would grow faster.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020050124e11o0000o\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
