\par\par \b \uc2 Discriminatory rules still haunt Chinese-Indonesians  \b0\par\par\uc2 Kurniawan Hari, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta  \par \uc2 755 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 February 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 For badminton legend Tan Joe Hok, 67, any discussion about discrimination against suku Tionghoa (the term used by many Chinese-Indonesians to describe themselves) is frustrating. Indeed, he was reluctant to recall all of the instances of discrimination suffered by him and his family.  \par \par \uc2 "It was very difficult for my children to enroll in schools. We, Chinese-Indonesians, are considered foreigners in our own homeland," he told The Jakarta Post recently.  \par \par \uc2 Tan Joe Hok, the All England champion in 1959 and a member of the victorious Thomas Cup teams in 1961 and 1964, refused to elaborate on the discrimination.  \par \par \uc2 He simply said that all he wanted was clarity from the government; whether Chinese-Indonesians are still required to obtain an SBKRI (the acronym for Indonesian citizenship certificates).  \par \par \uc2 Officially, the government in 1996 revoked the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  requiring Chinese-Indonesians to produce a SBKRI if they wanted to obtain documents such as ID cards, driver's licenses, passports and birth certificates.  \par \par \uc2 But a recent survey by Solidarity for the Nation (SNB) in five cities found Chinese-Indonesians were still required to produce SBKRIs.  \par \par \uc2 "Today, the situation is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . That is why we need clarity from the government," Tan Joe Hok added.  \par \par \uc2 When president Soeharto revoked the discriminatory \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 1996 expectations were high that it would be a starting point for an end to racial discrimination in the country.  \par \par \uc2 In 1998, president BJ Habibie issued a presidential instruction to end the official use of the phrases "indigenous Indonesians" and "non-indigenous Indonesians".  \par \par \uc2 Two years later, the government of president Abdurrahman Wahid revoked a \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  banning Chinese-Indonesians from celebrating their religious ceremonies and holidays.  \par \par \uc2 And president Megawati Soekarnoputri in 2002 declared the Chinese New Year, known here as imlek, a national holiday.  \par \par \uc2 This was all a relief for Chinese-Indonesians, who for decades had experienced discrimination.  \par \par \uc2 However, despite signals from the government that it was ending discrimination against Chinese-Indonesians, officials in the field continue to enforce discriminatory policies.  \par \par \uc2 Lawyer Frans Hendra Winarta said despite the revocation of the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the SBKRI, officials still asked Chinese-Indonesians to produce the certificate.  \par \par \uc2 "Since the practice lacks a legal basis, it just takes courage from Chinese-Indonesians to reject any demand to produce a SBKRI.  \par \par \uc2 "My last experience was when I extended my passport two months ago. The officials asked me to produce a SBKRI but I refused their demand. There must be courage on the part of Chinese-Indonesian," Frans told the Post.  \par \par \uc2 These discriminatory practices, which had a legal basis in various regulations, were inherited from the Dutch colonial rulers. The Dutch segregated the people based on ethnicity; that is Europeans, Arabs, East Asians (including Chinese) and the indigenous population. The indigenous people were treated inferior to the "second-class" Arabs and East Asians, and the "first-class" Europeans.  \par \par \uc2 Soelistyowati Soegondo, a member of the National Commission on Human Rights (Komnas HAM), said recently that today continued to complain about discrimination.  \par \par \uc2 "We continue to receive complaints from people. They want justice," she said.  \par \par \uc2 Minister of Justice and Human Rights Hamid Awaluddin has said that the government had revoked the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the SBKRI. He said the continued application of this \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  by offices in the field was the result of inconsistency in state apparatus.  \par \par \uc2 "We have revoked the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  but there are inconsistencies in the application," he said.  \par \par \uc2 Legislator Alvin Lie Ling Piao from the National Mandate Party (PAN) was not eager when asked to comment on discrimination against Chinese-Indonesians.  \par \par \uc2 He said the situation was improving for Chinese-Indonesians, and regional autonomy had encouraged several regions to put an end to all discriminatory practices.  \par \par \uc2 Local administrations in Surakarta and Semarang, both in Central Java, have said they wish to be pioneers in the abolishment of discrimination, especially in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  services.  \par \par \uc2 "As a nation we have to engage in some reflection. We have to ask ourselves whether Chinese-Indonesians have done their best for the country," Alvin said.  \par \par \uc2 Some rulings on Chinese-Indonesians:  \par \par \uc2 - Article 26 of the Constitution on citizenship differentiates between indigenous Indonesians and Indonesians of other races.<br> - Law No. 62/1958 on citizenship obliges Indonesian-born Chinese to carry documents not required for "indigenous" Indonesians.<br> - Presidential Decree No. 240/1966 obliges all those of Chinese descent to adopt Indonesian names.<br> - Presidential Instruction No. 37/1967 limits the education and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  opportunities for Chinese-Indonesians.<br> - Home Ministry Instruction No. 455.2-360/1968 regulates the construction of Chinese temples.  \par \par \uc2 Doc