\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Economy \highlight\uc2  grew by 5.13% in 2004: BPS   \b0\par\par\uc2 Urip Hudiono , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 509 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 February 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Despite pre-election jitters and a final-quarter slowdown, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2004 still managed to grow by 5.13 percent, continuing a steady four-year improvement, the Central Statistics Agency (BPS) said on Wednesday.   \par \par \uc2 The figure, which exceeded the initial target of 4.8 percent and 2003's growth of 4.1 percent, has pushed the nation's income per capita to Rp 10.64 million (US$1,181), from Rp 9.57 million the year before.   \par \par \uc2 The report shows that strong household consumption continued to be the main fuel of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  engine, making up about 66.54 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) -- the value of goods and services produced throughout the year.   \par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, investment and exports had managed to show a steady expansion and began to contribute more to the GDP growth, BPS head Choiril Maksum said.   \par \par \uc2 Most sectors in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  had reflected this overall growth, except for the mining sector, which had contracted by 4.61 percent, Choiril said.   \par \par \uc2 "The most significant growth was in the transportation and communications sector, at 12.70 percent," he said.   \par \par \uc2 Trailing further behind, the construction sector had expanded by 8.17 percent over the year, while financial services grew by 7.72 percent.   \par \par \uc2 With some 40 million people currently living on or below the poverty line, and 2.5 million new workers entering the country's job market each year, Indonesia still needs \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of more than 6 percent to soak up its unemployment.   \par \par \uc2 Estimates by economists show that each extra 1 percent of GDP growth per annum would create up to 400,000 new jobs.   \par \par \uc2 However, the country's improving investment and export markets boded well for the future, BPS social statistics official Rusman Heriawan said.   \par \par \uc2 "In previous years, consumption was the backbone of our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said. "However, we can see that investment growth in 2004 has outpaced growth in consumption."   \par \par \uc2 Consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew by 4.94 percent in 2004 while growth in investment reached 15.71 percent.   \par \par \uc2 However, in terms of total numbers, consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  still made up the lion's share of GDP, at about 66.5 percent, as against investment, 20.9 percent, while net-export earnings contributed the remaining 12.6 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's exports grew to an historic high of $69.71 billion last year, up 11.49 percent from the previous year, boosted by strong sales in non oil and gas commodities of palm oil, electronics, clothing, coal and tin.   \par \par \uc2 Still, analysts say much work is left to be done to boost more of growth in investment.   \par \par \uc2 Business remains poor here compared with Indonesia's regional competitors, with overseas investors steering clear of the country because of corruption in business, excessive red tape, higher relative costs of labor and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the legal system and security situation.   \par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, because of the strong consumption and improving investment and export trends, Rusman predicted this year's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target of 5.5 percent was attainable.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020050217e12h00008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picsc