\par\par \b \uc2 OIL PRICE HIKES TO PUSH UP INFLATION BY TWO PERCENT: OBSERVER   \b0\par\par\uc2 428 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 March 2005\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.   \par \par \uc2 Semarang, C Java, March 1 (ANTARA) - The fuel oil price hikes effective March 1, 2005, will cause this year's inflation rate to increase by two percent to eight percent, economist Dr FX Sugiyanto said here Tuesday.   \par \par \uc2 Sugiyanto told newsmen the increase in the inflation rate was merely based on an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  calculation and it could be higher or lower if psychological and socio-political factors had given contributions to the fuel oil price hike.   \par \par \uc2 The government announced the fuel oil price hikes Monday night (Feb.28) but kerosene which is widely consumed by poor families remains at its previous price of Rp700 per liter.   \par \par \uc2 Although the prices of goods and services had earlier increased, Sugiyanto said more impacts would be felt in two or three months' time after the announcement of the fuel oil price hikes.   \par \par \uc2 According to Sugiyanto who is a lecturer at Diponegoro University's \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Faculty in Semarang, the government should indeed raise the fuel oil prices instead of postponing the measure, and the increase should have actually been made \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  during Megawati Soekarnoputri's government.   \par \par \uc2 "If the measure to raise the fuel oil prices is postponed, it would prolong the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while prices of goods and services have earlier increased," he said.   \par \par \uc2 Thus, Sugiyanto disagreed with the executive board of university students (BEM) that opposed the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  which was intended to cut the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for fuel oil which had burdened the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  too much.   \par \par \uc2 He however reminded that the government makes the fuel oil price hike in one package in an effort to improve the \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  management and state oil company Pertamina's management.   \par \par \uc2 According to Sugiyanto, the country's potential in \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  was still considerable, and the \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Directorate General could always meet the target of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues because the target was still set below the existing potential.   \par \par \uc2 He opined that the effort to improve Pertamina's management in a transparent manner was a must as the people wanted to know the amount of Indonesia's oil exports and imports.   \par \par \uc2 He disclosed that the quality of oil exported by Indonesia was much better than that imported from Singapore's refineries of oil which was produced in Iran.   \par \par \uc2 Thus, he added, Indonesia should have enjoyed a windfall from the world oil price which once reached US$50 per barrel.   \par \par \uc2 On the kerosene price remaining at Rp700 per liter, he said this type of oil was consumed by poor families and thus the measure to set the price was right.   \par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020050302e13100008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
