\par\par \b \uc2 Communicating risks of disasters to insecure  \highlight22\uc2 public \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 Ardimas Sasdi , Jakarta   \par \uc2 935 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 April 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 In a terse, sharp remark on the sheer panic that enveloped Padang after a powerful quake jolted the province, an academic-cum-journalist colleague said, "Our society is sick. We need to do something".   \par \par \uc2 For the sake of politeness, I just nodded, although I saw the matter differently. It sounds like the all too common excuse by the government to shift the blame for its failure to protect its residents. West Sumatrans, like many other Indonesian ethnic groups, indeed posses local wisdom with regard to how they should react to dangerous situations, especially devastating natural disasters.   \par \par \uc2 The values however are not static, but evolve along with time and the nature of risks. For example, the resilience of already wary people will likely crumble in the face of reports of impending tsunamis or other disasters.   \par \par \uc2 The way residents of Padang reacted when a 6.7-magnitude quake jolted the city on April 10 -- three and a half months after the Aceh quake and tsunami, which wreaked havoc -- should be seen through this perspective.   \par \par \uc2 The images of the Aceh tsunami, showed over and over again on TV, was more powerful than logical reasoning for the people of Padang. Even those not directly affected by the tragedy like Jakartans, who previously frequented the beaches of Anyer and Carita, have chosen to visit resorts in mountain areas like Puncak since the tsunami and two quakes near Karakatau.   \par \par \uc2 "Some people were so afraid of another tsunami that they left behind valuables, like vehicles, which were necessary to take them to safer areas. On that day the streets leading up into hills were clogged by people and vehicles," a Padang resident said, adding that almost all 600,000 residents of the coastal city rushed out of their homes and fled to higher ground in a matter of minutes.   \par \par \uc2 The exodus turned Padang into a temporary ghost town. Except they left behind their sick relatives and small children, and put their fate God's hands.   \par \par \uc2 "The situation was so chaotic that even attendants at gas stations fled and left their jobs when they received "information" of the impending tsunami from motorists filling up their tanks. This condition left motorists in a dilemma. On one side they needed gas, but the could not fill their tanks. So some filled the tanks of their own cars," the resident of Padang explained.   \par \par \uc2 Intensive media coverage on natural disasters since the Aceh tsunami, some less than accurate, also have had serious ramifications on the business sector and the way the people view risks and expectations from the government.   \par \par \uc2 The number of visits by tourists to some areas is also down, but the media is not to blame for this gloomy trend. Foreign tourists, who made a great contribution to the Nias \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , can no longer be seen on the island's beaches. The drop in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity has forced locals to collect dried seaweed to eat, and search far and wide for potable water.   \par \par \uc2 Attempts to lure visitors back to tourist resorts is not easy. Tourist operators in Anyer and Carita on the Sunda Strait in Banten, complained that even though volcanology experts said that the Karakatau mountain's activity would not endanger Anyer beach, tourists' perceptions were hard to change.   \par \par \uc2 These cases demonstrated that the handling and communicating of risks to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially the people who have been battered by a series of calamities, is a mammoth task. But alas the government, which is always too late, has done very little in the way of a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  campaign to educate people about natural disasters.   \par \par \uc2 The theory of communication dictates that information proliferates amid \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Some are positive, but others are not, and even misleading, such as rumors spread by irresponsible parties to exploit chaotic conditions to create unrest or to commit crimes such as looting.   \par \par \uc2 The handling of information to an already vulnerable \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , who certainly have lost trust in the government, is not a simple task, but needs a multipronged approach. First and foremost is to regain the lost trust. Thus the government must make restoring the trust a priority.   \par \par \uc2 The next step is to build action plans, which involve all concerned parties like the media and a team of experts, and form a team of credible experts to implement these principles for the handling of risks.   \par \par \uc2 These measures must be done simultaneously with \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  education on risks, drills on disaster precautions and the promotion of local tradition, as has been the case of Simeulue island residents, who go to the beach and check the surface of water, to develop of an early warning system. Only 10 residents of Simeulue, the closest land mass to the epicenter of the quake, were killed in the Dec. 26 quake and tsunami, a minuscule figure compared to the number of victims in other areas.   \par \par \uc2 The people must also be made aware that irrational responses like panic and hysteria in the face of threats is not only unhelpful, but also creates new problems.   \par \par \uc2 Communicating risks to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  should also better reflect concerns of the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . And initiatives should also be developed to improve levels of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and media understanding about risk concepts and the need for the improvement of the accuracy of reporting of crises.   \par \par \uc2 In a climate of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and weak \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  trust, the management of information on risks should be conducted as openly, transparently and realistically as possible. When those things are done, costly crises have been prevented and the people have been served.   \par \par \uc2 The author is a staff writer of The Jakarta Post.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020050428e14s0000q\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
