\par\par \b \uc2 Life begins at 70 for batik designer Iwan Tirta  \b0\par\par\uc2 Bruce Emond , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta  \par \uc2 2,148 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 May 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 When it comes to spreading the good word about Indonesia in overseas handicraft and cultural expos, Iwan Tirta knows how to work a showroom to maximum effect.   \par \par \uc2 The country's ambassador of batik design, recruited for next week's Indonesia Handicraft Gallery in Tokyo in conjunction with President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono's state visit, is pulling out all the stops for the trip.   \par \par \uc2 On an afternoon last week, Iwan's staff packed up the finest examples of his works as the designer dutifully crouched in front of a swath of unfinished batik for documentation photos.   \par \par \uc2 He knows that it will take nothing short of the best to impress the sophisticated audience in a country he first visited in 1962.   \par \par \uc2 "You have to clobber them with all the finery you have," joked Iwan, borrowing the expression used by then president Soeharto when discussing his approach to dealing with political dissenters in the early 1990s.   \par \par \uc2 A veteran of many such campaigns, Iwan has been called upon to display Indonesia's unique textile heritage to a long list of dignitaries, from former British prime minister Margaret Thatcher to the Reagans, on their visits to these shores.   \par \par \uc2 His designs clothed the leaders at the APEC meeting here in 1994; even former 007 Roger Moore, during his stopover for UNICEF a couple of years ago, donned a couple of Iwan's shirts as he made the rounds.   \par \par \uc2 The image of the humble craftsman dutifully explaining the "exotic" craft of batik to a curious foreign audience is an ironic and amusing one for those who know Iwan.   \par \par \uc2 A highly educated, witty raconteur who can volunteer sage albeit blunt personal advice, and wickedly cut down to size the powers that be, Iwan straddles two different and contrasting worlds.   \par \par \uc2 A confirmed foodie, he knows his way around a spread, whether discussing spicy Padang food or the finer points of French cuisine. At home in Jakarta's finer dining establishments, he still loves to occasionally defy his doctor's orders about watching his sugar and sodium intake to sneak a meal at Trio, the simple cubbyhole of a restaurant near his home in Menteng, Central Jakarta, that has been a favorite spot since he tasted his first Nanking chicken there a half century ago.   \par \par \uc2 His choice of listening material in his car is equally eclectic, ranging from the clattering strains of Javanese gamelan to Maria Callas singing Aida ; his nightstand may include the waspish diary of English fashion maven Cecil Beaton, The Da Vinci Code or the latest biography of an Indonesian political figure.   \par \par \uc2 He also has the necessary pop culture savvy, as familiar with dangdut singer Inul Daratista, last year's infotainment "cause calibre", to the almost forgotten stars of Hollywood's yester-yesteryear. Mention hot actor-comic Tora Sudiro, and Iwan waxes on about his late mother, Pinky, who modeled for him.   \par \par \uc2 Iwan, who turned 70 on April 18, quipped that perhaps this article should be titled "the final stretch", but he is not ready to retire to a complacent dotage quite yet.   \par \par \uc2 The spirit is willing to continue bestowing his knowledge on others even if the flesh is, admittedly, weaker than it once was.   \par \par \uc2 But he still has his moments.   \par \par \uc2 He recently returned from a trip to Spain, the lone man among a group of women travelers. As others in the group supped on hotel fare, he went off with former journalist Herawati Diah on a jaunt through Seville's backstreets to find a decent plate of paella.   \par \par \uc2 "I feel fine, this is the thing, you know. I don't feel different from five years ago except, perhaps, the endurance," he said at his home-cum-boutique on Jl. Panarukan in Menteng.   \par \par \uc2 He suffered a mild stroke last year; he has made an excellent recovery, but he no longer attempts the "New Yorker walk" -- rapid paced, eyes focused on a distant target straight ahead -- that he adopted in the U.S. city where he spends several months each year.   \par \par \uc2 "Now when I see people walking like that, I think, oh my god, did I really walk like that! I don't want to take the risk of a fall, with brittle bones."   \par \par \uc2 For the past few years, Iwan has emphasized that he is no longer interested in "putting feathers in my cap" -- he has reached a point in his life where feeding the ego no longer takes center stage.   \par \par \uc2 He has enjoyed the trappings of success, but he is not interested in the ultimately self-defeating trap of keeping ahead of the pack. Glitzy fashion shows and the yearning to see his name splashed in big, bold letters in newspaper headlines are a thing of the past.   \par \par \uc2 He compares himself to the "good guys" of Javanese Ramayana and Mahabharata shadow plays, who start divesting themselves of their material possessions once the battle is won to adopt a humbler, more altruistic approach to life.   \par \par \uc2 "Now the main purpose in life for me is giving back what people have given me, and sharing whatever I have experienced. So many people supported me during my formative years, and now I can give back to people in general.   \par \par \uc2 "Mostly it's teaching, in the sense that I am asked my advice on this, acting as a consultant on that, on food, etiquette."   \par \par \uc2 He was born in Blora, East Java, to a Javanese father and a mother from West Sumatra. There were three older sisters from his father's first marriage, but Iwan was the baby of the family.   \par \par \uc2 It was a well-to-do family -- "I was born with not exactly a silver spoon in my mouth, but at least it was silver plated" -- with his father's job as a judge allowing the family to vacation within the region and to own a car.   \par \par \uc2 The family moved between cities in East Java due to his father's assignments -- from Blora to Bojonegoro and Madiun -- before being transferred to Jakarta during the Japanese occupation.   \par \par \uc2 Iwan talks about the eerie silence that descended on the city as the Japanese troops rolled in -- on bikes.   \par \par \uc2 With the continuing outcry about Japanese abuses in Asia during World War II, Iwan acknowledges that the years were difficult in what had been the Dutch model suburb of Menteng, where parts were cordoned off as concentration camps for the former colonists.   \par \par \uc2 As the Japanese kept the local population in the dark, taking over the airwaves and churning out propaganda, Iwan's family car was seized by the invading forces and jewelry appropriated. Tellingly, Iwan's mother began selling off pieces from her batik collection to make ends meet.   \par \par \uc2 Iwan says it is time for all sides to be realistic about what happened during the war years.   \par \par \uc2 "Actually, it was not like the Jews were treated in Europe, we weren't systematically eliminated. It was just a case of, 'If you're hungry, too bad. If you're sick, what can we do?' It (the fend-for-yourself attitude) was the killer."   \par \par \uc2 In his home, education (his mother also had an academic background) and social graces were emphasized.   \par \par \uc2 In the biographical section of his 1996 book Batik: A Play of Light and Shades , Iwan described his childhood as almost "Victorian", an environment in which children were seen but not heard, especially when his father was around.   \par \par \uc2 Iwan's father, who would eventually become a Supreme Court justice, made it a rule to eat alone: He told his children that they could dine at the same table as him when they had earned their university degrees.   \par \par \uc2 "In the younger years of my parents, education was the key to social mobility ... the Indonesian elite came up from the lower middle classes (through education). And, of course, in the land of the blind, you're king."   \par \par \uc2 It is this grounding in the importance of learning that has been the key to Iwan's success, allowing him to travel, move easily between contrasting worlds, and also to carve out his reputation as the most knowledgeable man in his field.   \par \par \uc2 First educated at the University of Indonesia, he studied law at the University of London under a Colombo Plan scholarship in the late 1950s, during which time his father died. He returned home in 1961, when his mother opened her home to young Indonesianists seeking a boardinghouse as they conducted research.   \par \par \uc2 Among them was Benedict Anderson, who encouraged Iwan to pursue his growing interest in documenting the craft of batik.   \par \par \uc2 In 1964, Iwan studied law at Yale University and later won an Adlai Stevenson scholarship to work at the United Nations in New York City.   \par \par \uc2 Throughout his life, he has always strived to "reinvent" himself, most notably in the 1970s when he gave up law to fully immerse himself in batik designing. He has since branched out into using batik motifs in silverware and ceramics.   \par \par \uc2 Iwan also took up bodybuilding in the same decade as he spent more time in his second home of New York City, saying he wanted to buck the stereotype of fashion designers as fey, limp-wristed types.   \par \par \uc2 Along with the success, there have been difficult times. He suffered horrific burns to his legs 30 years ago when someone carelessly tossed a cigarette into a sluice at his workshop, igniting the chemicals. A legal wrangle a couple of years ago almost cost Iwan his home before the matter was finally settled.   \par \par \uc2 His life has been lived among the country's most turbulent years, in which the only constant was the trepidation about what tomorrow would bring.   \par \par \uc2 "The thing that I deplore the most in my whole life is the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Even from childhood on, my father would say, 'When the war is over ....' But then the Dutch came back. And then we got independence ... and you could have 100,000 rupiah in the bank and the next morning it would be worth nothing ...."   \par \par \uc2 For a man for whom education has been so important, the current state of the country is saddening.   \par \par \uc2 "If you want \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  progress, it's all based on education. Are they able to read? Are they able to voice their opinion? And with education comes development of the country ...."   \par \par \uc2 Despite all the saber-rattling and cries to attack "arrogant" neighbors, Iwan laments how the country has fallen behind other nations in Southeast Asia.   \par \par \uc2 "It fills me with envy. You start to wonder, why are we so behind? It makes me so sad. When I go to Kuala Lumpur, I look at things, and think, 'Why can't we have that?'"   \par \par \uc2 This lack of education is to be found even in the highest corridors of power.   \par \par \uc2 "Our politicians, the level of education is hopeless. And when we talk about politicians we always talk about male politicians, we forget about our need for female politicians," said Iwan.   \par \par \uc2 His pursuit of knowledge has never ended; when he travels to a new land, as in his trip to Spain, he studies up on the local culture and learns a smattering of its language.   \par \par \uc2 "It doesn't matter what you read -- just read. At least you know. If you're an economist, don't just read about the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Read novels, read magazines. They will give you the necessary support to have a vision."   \par \par \uc2 The educational wasteland is fertile ground for the "one-eyed king syndrome", where slick-talking smooth operators can parlay their dubious talents into stunning success.   \par \par \uc2 "Oh, honey," he says with an arched eyebrow when mention is made of a designer known for his all-consuming efforts at self-promotion, including furnishing an accolade-heavy CV.   \par \par \uc2 Never married, Iwan quips he has a "don't-ask-don't-tell-\b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 " on his private life (he famously sidesteps the inevitable inquiries by saying his bachelorhood is his contribution to the government's efforts at population control).   \par \par \uc2 He is happy living with his gaggle of beloved pugs and devoted assistants, working at his efforts to preserve the country's cultural heritage and planning his next projects.   \par \par \uc2 Iwan, long past the age of aggressive pursuit of ambitions, still dreams of one day having a fashion show in the hallowed grounds of Versailles. For the immediate future, he is looking forward to a cruise to Alaska.   \par \par \uc2 His story is something to tell, and he may get around to penning his memoirs, a juicy proposition considering his vast knowledge of who's who and how they stooped to conquer.   \par \par \uc2 But it's here that his cultural background presents a stumbling block.   \par \par \uc2 "You know, there is my cosmopolitan veneer, but I am still Javanese," he told me once. "For Javanese, we don't mention what is in our hearts, especially not in writing. It is like showing our underwear to the world, like opening all the windows to your soul.   \par \par \uc2 "And that simply is not done."   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020050529e15t00006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
