\par\par \b \uc2 Pay rise for legislators?   \b0\par\par\uc2 Benget Simbolon Tnb. , Jakarta   \par \uc2 777 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 July 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) recently proposed a salary increase for its members of almost 300 percent from Rp 12 million to Rp 35.3 million.   \par \par \uc2 The proposal will be deliberated as part of the draft of next year's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and its approval seems inevitable.   \par \par \uc2 In fact, a number of \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  bodies in regencys and cities across the country have made similar requests. In Jakarta alone, legislators have enjoyed a pay rise of 320 percent since January from Rp 6.5 million to Rp 21 million per month.   \par \par \uc2 After they take up office, legislators are more interested in their salaries than the issues of the day.   \par \par \uc2 Some members claim to need additional funds to pay advisors, but the House already has a team of advisors who are ready to assist them.   \par \par \uc2 Others claim to need more money to improve their performance and enhance their relations with their constituents. Since their performance is related to other government agencies, why do they not also demand a pay rise for all members of related institutions?   \par \par \uc2 As matters stand, the 550 members of the House do not deserve to get a pay rise.   \par \par \uc2 First, their performance so far does not entitle them to a rise. After more than six months in office, they have only managed to pass a revision of the 2005 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . They were supposed to pass 55 bills this year, but so far not one has been passed. The 55 bills are among 284 drafts scheduled to be passed by the end of their term in 2009.   \par \par \uc2 For sure, people still remember the promises the legislators made during the election campaigns last year. When do they start working to realize them? Or are they too busy to recall the promises of their own parties?.   \par \par \uc2 Second, if we think of Indonesia as a company and House members as its employees, more light is shed on the issue. A company that is doing well considers rewarding its employees, a company facing hard times does not.   \par \par \uc2 Compared to other countries in the Southeast Asian region, Indonesia's business climate remains poor as investors are staying away due to its record of corruption, red tape, higher labor costs and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in its legal system and security situation.   \par \par \uc2 Because of the barriers, Indonesia has only undergone a shaky growth of about five percent, which is still two percentage points below the seven percent expected to be able to absorb the growing number of unemployed.   \par \par \uc2 According to National Development Planning Board (Bappenas) data, due to the slow growth of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the open unemployment rate over the last five years has been increasing from eight million (8.10 percent) in 2001, to 9.13 million (9.06 percent) in 2002, 9.53 million (9.50 percent) in 2003, 10.04 million (9.81 percent) in 2004 and is expected to be around 10.51 million (10.05 percent) this year.   \par \par \uc2 According to the Central Statistics Agency (BPS), total unemployment, including people who are earning less than the basic wage, has now reached some 40 million people.   \par \par \uc2 Of a population of 220 million people, 40 million are living under the poverty line. If the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to grow at a slow rate, that number will continue to increase.   \par \par \uc2 Due to poverty, for example, many families are unable to send their children to school or are forced to take their children out of school.   \par \par \uc2 For others, the situation is even worse. They are unable to provide their children with healthy food, or enough food, as evident in the malnutrition cases recently reported.   \par \par \uc2 Conditions are probably going to get worse due to the fuel crisis, which will very likely force the government to raise fuel prices to lessen the burden of the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The increasing prices of fuel, with global oil prices hovering at US$60 per barrel, will certainly increase the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Considering this, how can House members have the heart to ask for a pay rise? Why do they not, as the people's representatives, prioritize tackling the problems faced by the country?   \par \par \uc2 Do they not realize that Indonesia has been reduced to a poor country since it was hit by the multi-crisis of 1998?. Or has the get-rich-quick disease blurred their definitions of poverty and ethical behavior?   \par \par \uc2 Perhaps, if that is the case, then they are included in the group of people whose definition of poverty is as follows: Pak Dullah is a poor man: His driver is poor, his gardener is poor, and his family's babysitter is also poor.   \par \par \uc2 The author is a staff writer of The Jakarta Post.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020050725e17p0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
