\par\par \b \uc2 Tightening money supply   \b0\par\par\uc2 771 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 August 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) has tightened its monetary stance again as inflation seems to be rearing its ugly head amid the weakening rupiah against the American dollar, the steady rise in international oil prices to as high as US$64/barrel early last week and the increase in the U.S. Fed fund rate to 3.5 percent.   \par \par \uc2 The latest monthly meeting of the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's board of governors last week decided to increase the BI Rate by 25 basis points to 8.75 percent to address what it called the rising expectation of inflation among the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Cumulative inflation in the first seven months of this year already reached almost 6 percent.   \par \par \uc2 The upcoming inflationary pressures, as forecast by the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , should be so tremendously strong, otherwise it would not have changed the BI Rate at the risk of damaging the credibility of its inflation-targeting framework, which was launched in early July. The BI Rate was supposed to be effective as the nominal anchor for the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  until the end of September.   \par \par \uc2 The inflation- targeting framework, which relies heavily on inflation forecasts, aims monetary stance to influencing aggregate demands to be in line with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  capacity from the supply side. Put in another way, the current monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  aims at achieving the inflation target by influencing the future rate of inflation through \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  rather than monetary aggregates. This is the objective of the launching of the BI Rates in early July.   \par \par \uc2 But the falling rupiah rate and rising oil prices are indeed powerful ammunition for inflationary pressure as international inflation is immediately transmitted to the domestic market through higher import prices. Inflationary pressure has been closely linked with exchange rate developments because tradable goods comprise more than 60 percent of the consumer price index.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  explained that after closely monitoring the macroeconomic condition and its impact on the monetary prospects within the next few months, it foresaw higher inflation expectations among the general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially with the plans to raise administered prices of oil and electricity.   \par \par \uc2 The rupiah depreciated by 0.83 percent to Rp 9,810 against the dollar in July, and this trend could escalate if the oil prices remain above $60 a barrel for the rest of the year because of market jitters about Indonesia's worsening balance of payment prospects.   \par \par \uc2 If the government does not act immediately to raise significantly oil fuel prices, fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the whole year could explode to as high as Rp 130 trillion ($13 billion), or almost twice as large as the total budgeted by the government for the whole \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. On the other hand, rising oil fuel prices will trigger a chain of price increases in most goods.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  is indeed mired in a dilemma. Higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  certainly are not the panacea to curb inflation because price rises are not always a monetary phenomenon, especially in Indonesia's case, where administered prices bear significant weight in the consumer price index.   \par \par \uc2 However, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  should tighten its monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in anticipation of a credit crunch in the United States, otherwise portfolio investors may shift their investment in rupiah securities to dollar assets, because the U.S. Fed is expected to steadily increase its Fund rates to as high as 4 percent by the end of this year from 3.50 percent at present. A weaker rupiah would set off even higher inflation expectations.   \par \par \uc2 High inflation not only adversely affects investment and business operations, as it makes reasonable risk calculation almost impossible, but also hits hard the poor, the fixed, low income people. Moreover, it is impossible for \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to maintain the stability of the rupiah exchange rate in a high-inflation environment.   \par \par \uc2 The abrupt change in the BI Rate would not therefore adversely affect the credibility of the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's inflation targeting framework. In view of the likely strong inflationary pressures, especially in anticipation of the expected increases in administered prices (such as oil and power prices), changing the BI Rate could instead make the monetary instrument a more reliable guidepost for the making of inflation expectation among the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, in view of the novelty of the inflation-targeting framework as a monetary instrument and the learning process for its application, it would be well-advised for the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to set the inflation target in a reasonable range, not as a single, hard target. This range should be wide enough to accommodate the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  ahead regarding oil fuel and electricity prices and their impact on the prices of other goods. ---------   \pa