\par\par \b \uc2 Parta 1 of 2: The 2006 state  \highlight22\uc2 budget \highlight\uc2 : Out of wonderland?   \b0\par\par\uc2 Kahlil Rowter , Jakarta   \par \uc2 858 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 August 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 It has always been risky to put out government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  numbers, but now this is a perilous exercise. Forecast accuracy is an elusive goal. What we need is better risk management. Only then will we be convinced that the current difficuties are temporary.   \par \par \uc2 The government is still optimistic in putting 6.2 percent as 2006 gross domestic growth (GDP) rate. This will work if we believe the inflation-inspired rise in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will reverse course. Inflation this year is expected to rise to at least 8.5 percent mainly on the back of rise in energy prices. Depending on when fuel prices will be increased again, the effect might very well carry over to next year.   \par \par \uc2 Hence for inflation to tame down again will take a few more quarters in 2006. Even when \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are cut when this becomes evident, growth will not pick up again so fast. If we factor in an investment increase, perhaps from infrastructure related activities, its impact on inflation will come first before any growth effects appear. And in this construct we are already assuming smooth sectoral adjustments. Something not always wise to assume, especially for financial sector.   \par \par \uc2 The rupiah assumption also hinges on taming down present pressures stemming from fuel importation. To some extent this is conceivable when domestic fuel price matches its international counterpart. The wild cards are consumption-production \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and rupiah movements. With higher domestic fuel prices usage will eventually become more efficient. But the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  itself will take longer to disappear along with increase in oil production and refinery. Both will take longer than one year to achieve.   \par \par \uc2 Overall we see the assumptions as becoming more realistic, with a few caveats. The glaring exception is, of course, putting US$40 as oil price assumption. With current oil prices approaching $70 it is heroic to see next year's level at $40. Assuming $55-$60 is more realistic.   \par \par \uc2 However, if the central government assumes higher oil price it is will be forced to surrender more revenues to oil producing regions while at the same time bearing the full brunt of fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Hence it is politically easier to put a lower estimate now, lock in the regional government revenue handovers, and then raise fuel prices later.   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  rationality would like to see a higher oil price assumption and demand regions to bear part of the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But economics is and will always be a slave to political expediency. This will mean a fuel price increase sometime in 2006, which jeopardizes the inflation-interest-growth scenario.   \par \par \uc2 On the revenue side, \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue reveals a ratio to Gross domestic product (GDP) of "only" 13.4 percent which is marginal improvement from the trend in recent years. With a value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate of 10 percent, its current revenue level of less than 4 percent to GDP is a far cry from collection efficiency, even when we grant that a few goods are exempt from VAT.   \par \par \uc2 A lot more needs to be accomplished to increase revenues from VAT and other types of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . In fact a strong initiative from the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  office can bring light onto hitherto "hidden" parts of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The oil \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as discussed above, hinges on assuming oil price of $40 per barrel. If we simply use a discounted level to today's price at $60, this could mean reversion of oil \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to that estimated this year at around Rp 120 trillion. It will also open up the possibility of raising the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to current levels of at least Rp 26 trillion.   \par \par \uc2 The question then becomes how flexible is the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to come up with the extra money to cover this? Otherwise we will be left with another \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  as to when domestic fuel prices will again be increased.   \par \par \uc2 In itself this will raise expectations that inflation will again rise, probably bringing another interest hike from the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  and consequently \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth decline down the road.   \par \par \uc2 From these risks, we see a repeat of what took place in 2005, with no lessons learned. If only we can expect market players to be soothed once fuel prices are hiked this year. Unfortunately by looking at the 2006 assumptions and expecting another hike, this may not be possible.   \par \par \uc2 More likely players will connect the dots and simply assume at least a linear increase in inflation and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  from this to next year. Worse, if they start to question credibility of government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  making, the dot connecting exercise could end up with exponential rise in inflation and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This is something the government is well advised to avoid.   \par \par \uc2 Perception about \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policymaking is not helped by government officials at odds in the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  about crucial assumptions, outcomes and policies. It is time to face the music, disclose the actual difficulties faced by the government and to come up with a better plan hopefully in a more coherehent and cohesive manner.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is Head of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Fixed Income Research Mandiri Sekuritas. This article is personal opinion.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020050819e18j0000h\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
