\par\par \b \uc2 Unrealistic 2006  \highlight22\uc2 budget \highlight\uc2 : The damage has been done   \b0\par\par\uc2 David E. Sumual , Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,229 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 August 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 In a well-constructed speech, President Susilo B. Yudhoyono unveiled the 2006 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  proposal in his first annual address to the nation last week. Unfortunately, his impressive speaking style cannot of course be a panacea for the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems, particularly high oil prices.   \par \par \uc2 As mentioned in the president's speech, the major risk in the 2006 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be the stubbornly high global oil prices that will force the government to further cut domestic fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Despite the risk of fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  blowing out the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , there is however no dramatic change in the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  priority in 2006. The government is likely to spend as much as Rp 68.4 trillion, or about 12 percent of the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , on the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- or more than twice the amount budgeted for education expenditures. And considering the government's optimistic assumption on global oil prices, outlays for fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  could be much higher than the expected projection if world oil prices still hover way above the US$40/barrel, assumed for 2006.   \par \par \uc2 The national \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as well as foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2006 will thus remain vulnerable and increasingly at the mercy of international oil-price fluctuations.   \par \par \uc2 More worryingly, such a condition might last at least to the medium-term with Indonesia being a net oil importer. Moreover, the government has sent a signal that further cuts in consumer fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  will only occur at the beginning of 2006. As such, like a deja vu, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  may again face similar problems to the ones the country faced when fuel prices were raised in March 2005.   \par \par \uc2 The impact of higher fuel prices on business \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  plans, inflation and monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Indonesia will be like those in the second quarter of 2005. As reported by the Central Statistics Agency, both rising fuel prices and higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  have created headwinds and slowed the growth momentum in the second quarter. Second quarter GDP growth slowed to 5.5 percent from 6.2 percent in the first quarter as consumers apparently felt the inflationary pinch and curbed their \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 At the same time, higher oil prices also weighed on business investment. With inflation starting to creep up, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  had no other option but to tighten its monetary stance -- \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  has gradually raised its benchmark rates from 7.42 percent when the government decided to hike fuel prices to 8.75 percent now.   \par \par \uc2 And when \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  started to rise, more and more private businesses postponed their investment in capital goods, thus taking some of the steam out of the second quarter \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the government's plan to raise consumer fuel prices again in January 2006 has hit the financial markets. The damage has been done in the stock and bonds market. The Jakarta Composite Index has tumbled 8.8 percent over the past two weeks to its lowest level of 1087.9 in almost three months. At the same time, the rupiah, which hit a three-and-a-half year low of 9,975 to the dollar on Aug. 19, has lost 6.8 percent of its value against the dollar this year. Even worse, the rupiah depreciation took place although the monetary authority has sacrificed around 15 percent of its foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  since April 2005 to defend the local unit.   \par \par \uc2 Although fuel price hikes make sense from a \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  standpoint, the president may still harbor concerns over the political backlash and the negative impact on his popularity. Given his personal traits, Susilo will not want to break his earlier pledge to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  that the government would endeavor not to raise fuel prices again this year. However, this does not change the unpalatable reality of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  distress if it still bears the higher cost of oil to cushion Indonesians from external developments.   \par \par \uc2 Assuming an average oil price of $60/barrel, the country's fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  could reach Rp 126 trillion in 2005 and the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  would reach Rp 45 trillion. Under the $65/barrel scenario, fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  would swell to Rp 140 trillion, or nearly double the Rp 76.5 trillion budgeted for in the 2005 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 To cover the around Rp 21-27 trillion financing gap (assuming oil prices hover around $60-65/barrel till the end of the year), the government plans to take a number of measures including the issuance of new bonds, privatization and asset divestment. However, issuing bonds, privatization and sales of state assets in a bearish financial market are not supposed to be a priority.   \par \par \uc2 This is a risky option. If investors are uninterested in the government's plans to issue bonds and sell assets, Indonesia might again suffer oil shortages in the fourth quarter at the latest as the country would not have the funds to finance oil imports.   \par \par \uc2 It appears that the financial markets may continue to remain under pressure in the next five months prior to the government's actual decision to raise fuel prices. In the time being, the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in terms of the size and the exact timing of fuel price hikes may prompt "speculative motives" with rogue traders piling up subsidized fuels and opportunist traders raising their prices.   \par \par \uc2 Accordingly, such speculative behavior would create a cost-push inflation spiral in the months before the announcement, forcing the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to jack up benchmark \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  beyond the 8.75 percent level today.   \par \par \uc2 Given the heightening \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , there is also the risk that the capital outflow from foreign portfolio investors would cause the rupiah and the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  to tumble further. With \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  continuing to intervene in the currency market in the next five months, the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  could plunge below $30 billion, creating a negative perception that the forex \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  are not sustainable and would not be enough to defend the rupiah.   \par \par \uc2 At the same time, domestic companies may reschedule their investment plans, waiting for inflationary developments -- at least until the second quarter of 2006 after the government cuts the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The infrastructure summit that will be held in November may again fail as the first one early this year as investors are still in wait-and-see mode. Due to the prospect of heightening inflation and a beleaguered rupiah, most infrastructure investment may hinge on Indonesia's political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  developments beyond January 2006. As such, expectations that infrastructure investment will pour into the country in 2006 will be as unrealistic as the previous hopes that it would materialize in 2005.   \par \par \uc2 As such, it would actually be better for the government to cut the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  sooner rather than later. The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is subject to high risks if the government leaves the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  open and unhedged against world oil price fluctuations.   \par \par \uc2 Equally important, reverting again to the MOPS (Mean of Platts Singapore) as was done in 2003 to allow fuel prices to fluctuate in reference to the international standard should be a medium term objective. A strategic energy \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that may determine Indonesia's existence in the future should not again be exploited as a catalyst to boost popularity at the expense of the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sustainability.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is an analyst at the Danareksa Research Institute. This article represents his personal views.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020050823e18n0000p\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
