\par\par \b \uc2 Temporary relief for rupiah  \b0\par\par\uc2 812 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 September 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 The tighter money policies launched by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) on Tuesday, though rather overdue, have succeeded in shoring up the rupiah, which earlier fell to a five-year low of Rp 11,800 to the American dollar in the morning, to Rp 10,525 at the afternoon close. The local unit strengthened further to Rp 10,400 on Wednesday.  \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  raised its BI Rate by 75 basis points to 9.5 percent and its one-week overnight rate by 100 basis points to 8.5 percent and signaled a steep rise shortly in banks' compulsory reserve requirements at the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  and more intensive monitoring of foreign exchange transactions.  \par \par \uc2 All this aims at soaking up excess liquidity on the market and consequently reduce the ammunition for speculative trading on the local unit.  \par \par \uc2 President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono's special pronouncement on Tuesday that he and the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be introducing on Wednesday night a new package of concerted measures to beef up the rupiah also help allay the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's concern that the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -making machinery was in disarray.  \par \par \uc2 The President seemed to have realized that the daily operations of the financial market run on perceptions and not on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals that change on a monthly basis. Market perceptions can change from day to day because they are formed by information and statements from the government and political leaders.  \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  is really in a dilemma about how it manages the rupiah rate. The interest rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can be used only sparingly in view of its devastating impact on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , in view of the Rp 647 trillion (US$65 billion) in government bonds already issued. Much higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would also sabotage the nascent consumption-fueled recovery and further choke businesses.  \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  is also prudent for having refrained from too deep intervention into the market when the rupiah came under strong speculative attacks over the last two weeks because such a measure would waste the limited stock of its precious foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- worth about $32 billion.  \par \par \uc2 After all, the root cause of the fall is the negative market sentiment with regards to the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -making capability and its \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sustainability.  \par \par \uc2 A stronger enforcement of the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's ruling of April 2000 on foreign exchange (forex) transactions is also welcomed. The ruling requires all citizens and foreigners holding stay permits and Indonesians residing overseas to submit to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  through their banks much more detailed report documents on every forex transaction in excess of $10,000. This up-to-date reporting will provide the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  with accurate, comprehensive and timely data on forex deals to enable it to have a better view of the position of the external balance and international investment, a prerequisite for devising effective monetary policies.  \par \par \uc2 Highly commendable though was that the government, in spite of the devastating impact of the rupiah's free-fall, did not resort to slapping forex controls as these would be draconian measures that could cause total panic and chaos.  \par \par \uc2 As the President observed on Tuesday, the current condition has little resemblance to the situation that preceded the 1998 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political crisis.  \par \par \uc2 What we are facing now is a crisis of confidence in the government and its \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  management that set off a run on the rupiah as people scrambled to protect their savings and rupiah assets. What has been taking place in the currency market since Aug. 18 is a flight to quality but it is not yet a flight to safety -- as was the panic that occurred in early 1998 when people dumped their rupiah at whatever rate for the dollar.  \par \par \uc2 However, this crisis, if not resolved once and for all, could be self-fulfilling and escalate into a panic.  \par \par \uc2 Monetary measures by the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  alone will not be enough to maintain a stable rupiah at the desired level of 9,500 for this year and 9,400 for next year unless the government acts firmly and immediately to remove the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  about its \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  management.  \par \par \uc2 The package of measures President Susilo must announce should therefore stipulate: Clear-cut, definitive scheduling for the phasing-out of fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  by gradually floating domestic fuel prices on international market quotations; a credible mechanism of social safety nets for the poor to help them weather the general price rises within the coming months; and more concrete measures to improve the investment climate and help businesses cut costs.  \par \par \uc2 Anything short of this package would leave the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  highly vulnerable to high oil price fluctuations, which are entirely beyond the government's control.  \par \par \uc2 As we have repeatedly argued in this column, the billions dollars wasted annually for fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the middle and high-income group could have been invested far more usefully in education, health services and rural infrastructure.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020050901e1910000k\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
