\par\par \b \uc2 Government gears up to bite the bullet  \b0\par\par\uc2 Vincent Lingga , The  Jakarta Post, Jakarta  \par \uc2 860 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 September 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 The initially negative market reaction to the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  agenda of President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono could soon turn into positive sentiment as technical details on how and when the reforms will be implemented begin to be unveiled on Monday.  \par \par \uc2 The market, predictably, was disappointed with the package of measures on \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary management, energy and investment Susilo unveiled last Wednesday because they lacked specifics and were not as bold as expected.  \par \par \uc2 Nothing was actually new about the "new \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  directives" -- in fact they had always been central to the reform package prescribed for Indonesia by the International Monetary Fund between 1998 and 2003.  \par \par \uc2 Many analysts were even puzzled over the circumstances in which the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  agenda was decided. The package was first deliberated in a plenary Cabinet session on Tuesday night but was later fine-tuned by a smaller team of ministers on Wednesday.  \par \par \uc2 The absence of chief economics minister Aburizal Bakrie from the final process, and from the grandstanding ceremony in which President Susilo announced the major policies in a nationwide television address on Wednesday afternoon, raised many eyebrows and strengthened speculation about an imminent Cabinet reshuffle.  \par \par \uc2 Why did Susilo hasten the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  announcement without waiting for the return of Vice President Jusuf Kalla? A move that unnecessarily raised questions amid the mounting demand for the replacement of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team of the Cabinet.  \par \par \uc2 After all, Kalla, who chairs the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team, had decided to cut short his visit to China and entirely canceled his engagements in Japan to be able to return to Jakarta on Thursday morning.  \par \par \uc2 Susilo's move could nevertheless be understood if it was set against the immensely intense pressures he was facing due to the steady melting of the rupiah since mid-August. This situation had forced the President either to act immediately or at least to decide on and announce something to help calm the market, otherwise the crisis of confidence in the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  management could have escalated into panic.  \par \par \uc2 But the Cabinet meeting Susilo again convened on Thursday -- also attended by Vice President Kalla, chief \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  minister Bakrie and almost all members of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team seemed able to repair some of the damage caused by the President's haphazard showmanship the day before.  \par \par \uc2 The more conducive would it have been for the rupiah and macroeconomic stability if the technical details for the action plan on \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary management, energy and investment had been voted on by the market as economically and politically feasible.  \par \par \uc2 The Cabinet's decision to propose to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  on Monday several scenarios on how to phase out fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which could explode to almost US$14 billion this year, is quite strategic. Such a move would prevent political turbulence as observed last March, when the government raised fuel prices by about 30 percent.  \par \par \uc2 Anyway, the new fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will exact major changes in the current and next year's state budgets, and all this process has to be approved by the House.  \par \par \uc2 The President's directive that the gradual removal of fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  should be started only after a credible social-safety net mechanism to compensate the poor is in place is similarly vital to prevent social unrest and to minimize protests and demonstration. The government should indeed ensure fairness by protecting the poorest segment of society from the brunt of higher prices.  \par \par \uc2 Therefore, as the President has hinted, the phasing out of fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  could begin only after October. November (after the Idul Fitri celebrations) may be the most appropriate time for ushering in the painful measure because the government needs more time to establish a credible social-safety net program and to precondition the people to the brunt.  \par \par \uc2 Raising fuel prices this month or in October (the fasting month) after the 29 percent increase last March could be political suicide for Susilo's government.  \par \par \uc2 The next two months are more than enough time for the government and the House to deliberate and agree on amendments to the current and next year's budgets to accommodate the new fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 The next few weeks also will be sufficient time for the government, business leaders, including bus companies, to discuss and calculate the impact of the higher fuel prices and work out what additional reforms are still urgently needed to cut the costs of doing business in order to offset the higher costs of energy and to further stimulate investment.  \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  needs more time to introduce additional monetary measures to cope with anticipated stronger inflationary pressures after October.  \par \par \uc2 These preparations are all necessary to prevent a reaction of panic. At a time when many people are still suffering from the brunt of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis and millions of others are either unemployed or underemployed, additional burdens stemming from higher fuel prices could easily incite \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  anger.  \par \par \uc2 Massive street demonstrations, such as those in early 2003 and last March, would only make things murkier, injecting a factor of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This in turn could press down the rupiah exchange rate and set off a vicious circle within the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020050905e19500008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
