\par\par \b \uc2 'High royalties, high  \highlight22\uc2 taxes \highlight\uc2  not attractive to investors'   \b0\par\par\uc2 888 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 November 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Since the monetary crisis hit Indonesia in 1997, no major mining companies have applied to get concession rights to explore and exploit the rich minerals hidden in the country's earth bed. The Jakarta Post 's Leony Aurora talked with Newmont Pacific Nusantara's new president director Noke Kiroyan , who is also a member of the National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery Committee (KPEN) in charge of mining activities, on the proposed mining bill as well as investment in the sector. The following is an excerpt from the interview:   \par \par \uc2 Question : The \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  is deliberating a bill to replace the current law on mineral and coal mining, which is already 28 years old. What do you hope to get from the proposed draft law?   \par \par \uc2 Answer : We hope to get not just a mining law but one that is investor-friendly. We, in the KPEN, have requested the Ministry of Energy and Mineral Resources to maintain the proposed law within the road map set by the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin). The road map was also adopted by the President within his working plan.   \par \par \uc2 An investor-friendly mining law would be one where the legal basis for concession right was a contract, not a license. A license can be annulled by one party -- if the license giver decides to revoke the permit, the license holder has no recourse, no way of appealing.   \par \par \uc2 A contract, on the other hand, binds two parties and cannot be revoked by one or the other separately. A contract is stronger and thus is the preference of mining companies. This is also included in Kadin's road map.   \par \par \uc2 It would be regretful if the legal basis for mining services was a license, as currently being discussed, because many major mining companies would steer clear of investing here.   \par \par \uc2 We have tried contracts, which are used at present.   \par \par \uc2 Why do we want to try something other than a method that has been proven able to attract investors? The several drafts on the mining law have drifted from accommodating contracts, then licenses, then back to contracts, and so on. And the current one in the House accommodates licenses. Hopefully the House will hear our concerns.   \par \par \uc2 Sometimes people argue that other countries use licenses as well as or instead of contracts. Our argument to counter this is that Indonesia needs to attract investments. For the last eight years, there have been virtually no major movements and to get out of this situation, we have to make the mining sector more attractive. If it's a license, considering past experiences here, it won't be appealing to investors.   \par \par \uc2 If Indonesia had a good reputation of being a country with excellent legal certainty, perhaps the investors would not worry too much about whether it was a license or a contract.   \par \par \uc2 We don't know of the progression of the deliberation of the bill, as it seems to be stuck at the House. We haven't heard anything and even before the recess, there was little activity to discuss this. So I am not optimistic that we will get a new mining law this year.   \par \par \uc2 What else can be improved to boost investment in the mining sector?   \par \par \uc2 When we talk of investment in general, one of the most important things is legal certainty. How to make people confident that the legal conditions here can be trusted.   \par \par \uc2 What could also be attractive is if \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  requirements were nailed down in the contracts. With such a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , it would be clear how high \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  were at the beginning of mining activities.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  may be higher than applicable generally at a given moment, such as what happened with the first generation of coal miners, but as we could estimate the amount beforehand, we would get clear calculations on the costs. An \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  level of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  creates difficulties in making financial calculations.   \par \par \uc2 How about royalties?   \par \par \uc2 The government should pay attention to the condition of royalties applied in other countries. The tendency is that royalties around the world are going down. If we insist on high royalties and \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , of course it would not be attractive.   \par \par \uc2 Several countries now do not even apply royalties and get revenues only from the respective miners' income \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We, on the other hand, apply both high royalties and high \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Of course, when there are two similar deposits here and elsewhere, investors will go to where the royalties and \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  are lower.   \par \par \uc2 Do you have any plan to request concession rights to explore other areas?   \par \par \uc2 Not at the moment. Investors are adopting a wait-and-see attitude amid the present \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . As long as the new mining law is not finished, investors will not go into green fields. The development of areas that they already hold the concession rights for, however, will continue.   \par \par \uc2 What does Newmont plan to do in Indonesia next year?   \par \par \uc2 We are planning to develop the Elang site, about 40 kilometers east from our open-pit mine in Batu Hijau but still within our concession area in Nusa Tenggara.   \par \p