\par\par \b \uc2 Property for foreigners   \b0\par\par\uc2 668 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 November 2005\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Property analysts and developers share the same pessimistic projection that demand for all kinds of property will decline as the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to raise \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to cope with strong inflationary pressures and with a four-year low in consumer confidence.   \par \par \uc2 This negative market sentiment, we think, is partly responsible for the revisiting of an old issue within the property industry -- the ban on foreign nationals owning property in Indonesia, as stipulated in Law No.5/1960 concerning land ownership. The law provides five kinds of rights over land and buildings, but foreign nationals are entitled to only three of them, namely the right to use, the right to cultivate and the right to build.   \par \par \uc2 And even these rights can only be exercised for a certain period of time, ranging from 25 to 35 years, extendable for another 25-35 years under strict requirements, thereby putting investors at the mercy of the National Land Agency, which unfortunately is not included among the most efficient of government institutions in our country.   \par \par \uc2 Property developers and analysts are hoping that easing restrictions on foreign nationals owning property would partly offset the slackening demand from domestic consumers. Moreover, they argue that the reasons for imposing such severe limitations are no longer sensible and logical in the current era of globalization. The drafting of the highly restrictive land law in 1960 -- only 15 years after the nation's independence from colonial domination that lasted hundreds of years -- is understandable to an extent as the politicians of the time were still highly xenophobic of anything related to foreign presence.   \par \par \uc2 However, the core issue here is much broader than simply stoking foreign demand for property to offset the expected decline in demand from domestic consumers.   \par \par \uc2 The ban on foreign nationals owning property in Indonesia has long been a major disincentive to investment from overseas, notably small and medium enterprises. Analysts have warned that Indonesia has failed to attract many foreign small and medium-scale investors -- who are precisely the kind of businesses the country needs due to the labor-intensive nature of their operations -- because of the overly restrictive regulations on them owning property and the consequent legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by these excessively restrictive regulations.   \par \par \uc2 The restrictions and the arduous bureaucratic and regulatory procedures to obtain the limited right of use, right to cultivate and right to build not only causes a high degree of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  but also punitively high costs.   \par \par \uc2 In Bali, for example, quite a number of retirees from Europe and the United States who would like to spend the rest of their lives on the island of gods are forced to use an Indonesian nominees in an attempt to secure their property (homes), circumventing the ban but risking becoming embroiled in disputes or being cheated at some point.   \par \par \uc2 Easing the restrictions on foreign nationals owning property would serve to eliminate some of the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  of property ownership in this country.   \par \par \uc2 One should not dread of the possibility of foreign nationals becoming powerful landlords, because we are not talking about lifting the restrictions on rights of use or the right to cultivate and the right to build that may involve hundreds or thousands of hectares of land for mining or plantations.   \par \par \uc2 What property developers and analysts have been recommending since the 1980s is the lifting of the ban on foreign nationals buying and owning residential property. What risk is there to either the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  or national security if foreign nationals are allowed to own apartments/condominiums or luxury houses in Bali and other resort areas?   \par \par \uc2 On the contrary, allowing foreign nationals to own homes will not only strengthen the demand for residential property, but will also create legal certainty and will make overseas investors feel as though they are really welcome here.   \par \par \uc2 This is the point the government should take up in the bill on investment, which will soon be proposed to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  to unify the 1967 foreign investment law and the 1968 domestic investment law.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020051130e1bu0000n\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Negotiation for Gas Supply for Kujang Meets Failure   \b0\par\par\uc2 303 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 December 2005\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2005 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Negotiation with PT Odira Energy Persada facilitated by the Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs to get 17 million feet cubic of gas per day for Kujang IA fertilizer plant has met failure.   \par \par \uc2 The management of PT Pupuk Kujang is accused of showing slow response to opportunities to get gas, making Odira sell the gas to other consumer.   \par \par \uc2 "Odira finally sells the 17 million feet cubic of has to other consumer, leaving us only with 3.5 million feet cubic of gas per day," revealed Deputy Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs Edy Putra Irawadi to Bisnis yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 With this failure, Kujang IA fertilizer plant again faces \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in production next year following that the gas supply contract with the state oil company (Pertamina) would expire at the end of December this year.   \par \par \uc2 However, the condition of insufficient gas supply will last only for a year since Kujang has already signed a contract with British Petroleum Indonesia to receive gas supply in 2007.   \par \par \uc2 Previously, Edy was optimistic that the government would seal a deal with Odira. (Bisnis, November 17)   \par \par \uc2 With Kujang plant out of operation next year, the national fertilizer industry will face a difficult year since PIM fertilizer factory has also been out of operation due to lack of gas supply.   \par \par \uc2 On the other hand, President Director of PT Pusri Holding Dadang H. Kodri insured that the urea fertilizer supply to farmers next year would be sufficient since the national production of 5.3 million tons of fertilizer would be enough to meet the demands of 4.3 million tons.   \par \par \uc2 "However, if the government doesn't change the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  pattern, it will be certain that the fertilizer industry will suffer from losses," he added. (05/rahayuningsih/roni yunianto) (redaksi@bisnis.co.id)   \par \par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020051202e1c200003\par }\par \b \uc2 Search Summary\b0\par \par  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx2000\clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx9072\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Text\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \li50\uc2 (economic or economy) and (uncertain or uncertainty or uncertainties) and (policy or public or tax or taxation or taxes or taxed or spending or expenditure or fiscal or stimulus or budget or deficit or national debt or tariff or subsidies or subsidy or Bank Indonesia or central bank or re